From: Shimshony <vsahshim@netvision.net.il>
Subject: Rinderpest - Russia
Re your message of 8 October - it seems that you have mentioned Moldavia by
mistake. The outbreak occurred in Russia, Amur region. There is however, an
OIE report on Classical Swine Fever in Moldavia (OIE Dis.Inf. Vol 11 No 38,
and probably later as well).
---
A.Shimshony
***
[We apologise for this confusion and stupidity. The correct posting
follows. - Mod.MHJ
OIE, Paris, 2 October, 1998
RINDERPEST IN RUSSIA
Lifting of the restriction measures
See also: 28 August 1998
Follow-up report No. 1
Text of a fax received on 1 October 1998 from Dr V.M. Avilov, Chief of the
Main Veterinary Department, Ministry of Agriculture, Moscow:
End of previous report period: 24 August 1998 (see Disease Information, 11
[34, 115, dated 28 August 1998).
End of this report period: 30 September 1998.
Up-dated information on the number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible 150
cases 70*
deaths 42
destroyed 7
slaughtered 21
* 54 calves under 18 months old and 16 cows.
Diagnostic tests used: serology, PCR and inoculation tests.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
B. Mode of spread: common grazing.
All sick animals were slaughtered on 22 August 1998, and no new cases of
rinderpest have occurred since that date. All restriction measures were
lifted on 1 October 1998.
--
ProMED-mail
e-mail: promed@usa.healthnet.org
......................................mhj/es
